hands_on_practices.problem:
A unimolecular hydrogen-transfer reaction has a single negative-curvature mode at the transition state whose magnitude is reported by vibrational analysis as a wavenumber $	ilde{
u}^\ddagger = 1400\,\mathrm{cm^{-1}}$. In semiclassical rate theory, the temperature at which deep tunneling sets in (the crossover temperature) is defined by the criterion that the lowest nonzero thermal (Matsubara) frequency equals the absolute value of the transition-state barrier curvature frequency. Starting from this criterion and from the relationships between angular frequency, linear frequency, and spectroscopic wavenumber, derive an expression for the crossover temperature $T_c$ in terms of $	ilde{
u}^\ddagger$ and fundamental constants. Then evaluate $T_c$ for $	ilde{
u}^\ddagger = 1400\,\mathrm{cm^{-1}}$. Finally, based on the small-parameter structure of the Wigner tunneling correction as a high-temperature expansion in powers of $\hbar \omega^\ddagger/(k_B T)$, briefly assess whether Wigner’s correction is appropriate at $T = 298\,\mathrm{K}$ for this reaction, and justify your assessment.

Use the speed of light $c$, the reduced Planck constant $\hbar$, and the Boltzmann constant $k_B$ symbolically in your derivation, and do not substitute numerical values until the final numerical evaluation step. Express the crossover temperature in Kelvin and round your numerical result to three significant figures.
